Both done. Resizing now happens on a canvas before upload, and honestly the ordering bug was a fun one: we were sorting photos by when their upload finished, and since files go up in parallel, a small photo uploaded last could finish first and jump the queue. The order looked random because it effectively was. Photos are now sorted by the capture timestamp embedded in the image metadata, which matches the order you actually took them in. For files with no capture time — screenshots, or images edited in another app that stripped their metadata — we fall back to the file's modified time, so they slot in roughly where you'd expect instead of clumping at the front of the entry. Here's the gist of the reader:

```js
async function captureTime(file) {
  const tags = await exifr.parse(file, ['DateTimeOriginal']);
  return tags?.DateTimeOriginal ?? file.lastModified;
}
```

Uploads also show a per-file progress bar and a '3 of 10 uploaded' running counter now, so long batches read as steady progress rather than silence.

Shipped, and the difference is immediately visible on a throttled connection. Panning now feels like sliding over a painted surface instead of chasing white squares: the ring prefetch means the next screenful is usually resident before you reveal it, and revisiting an area you already crossed is instant because it comes straight from the cache. The prefetch logic is small — for every visible tile we enqueue its eight neighbors at low priority, so real viewport requests always jump the queue:

```js
for (const t of visibleTiles) {
  for (const n of neighbors(t)) queue.push(n, PRIORITY_LOW);
}
```

I also handled zooming, which had the same flash in a worse form: when you zoom in, we now keep the stretched tile from the previous zoom level underneath until the sharper one arrives, so the map goes briefly blurry instead of briefly blank. Blurry-then-sharp is how a paper map feels under a magnifying glass; blank-then-pop is how bugs feel. The fade-in on arriving tiles rounds it out.

When a cluster can't be split by zooming because its photos genuinely share one location, a click plays the fan-out: the bubble blooms into individual pins arranged in a ring, each connected to the center by a hairline leg, spaced so none of them overlap. Up to eight pins form a single ring; more than that adds a second, wider ring rather than crowding the first. Clicking anywhere else on the map folds the fan back into its bubble. The geometry is just even angular spacing:

```js
const angle = (2 * Math.PI * i) / count;
pin.offset = [Math.cos(angle) * r, Math.sin(angle) * r];
```

Each fanned pin behaves like a normal one — popup with the photo, its caption, and a link to its entry — so the ring is a temporary reading arrangement, not a different kind of object you have to learn.
